533:     /**
534:      * Returns the set of IDs for {@link Node}s to which fetch requests should <em>not</em> be sent.
535:      *
536:      * <p>
537:      * When a partition has buffered data in {@link FetchBuffer}, that means that at some point in the <em>past</em>,
538:      * the following steps occurred:
539:      *
540:      * <ol>
541:      *     <li>The client submitted a fetch request to the partition's leader</li>
542:      *     <li>The leader responded with data</li>
543:      *     <li>The client received a response from the leader and stored that data in memory</li>
544:      * </ol>
545:      *
546:      * But it's possible that at the <em>current</em> point in time, that same partition might not be in a fetchable
547:      * state. For example:
548:      *
549:      * <ul>
550:      *     <li>
551:      *         The partition is no longer assigned to the client. This also includes when the partition assignment
552:      *         is either {@link SubscriptionState#markPendingRevocation(Set) pending revocation} or
553:      *         {@link SubscriptionState#markPendingOnAssignedCallback(Collection, boolean) pending assignment}.
554:      *     </li>
555:      *     <li>
556:      *         The client {@link Consumer#pause(Collection) paused} the partition. A paused partition remains in
557:      *         the fetch buffer, because {@link FetchCollector#collectFetch(FetchBuffer)} explicitly skips over
558:      *         paused partitions and does not return them to the user.
559:      *     </li>
560:      *     <li>
561:      *         The partition does not have a valid position on the client. This could be due to the partition
562:      *         awaiting validation or awaiting reset.
563:      *     </li>
564:      * </ul>
565:      *
