134:      * Draining a {@link CompletedFetch} will signal that the data has been consumed and the underlying resources
135:      * are closed. This is somewhat analogous to {@link Closeable#close() closing}, though no error will result if a
136:      * caller invokes {@link #fetchRecords(FetchConfig, Deserializers, int)}; an empty {@link List list} will be
137:      * returned instead.
138:      */
139:     void drain() {
140:         if (!isConsumed) {
141:             maybeCloseRecordStream();
142:             cachedRecordException = null;
143:             this.isConsumed = true;
144:             recordAggregatedMetrics(bytesRead, recordsRead);
145: 
146:             // we move the partition to the end if we received some bytes. This way, it's more likely that partitions
147:             // for the same topic can remain together (allowing for more efficient serialization).
148:             if (bytesRead > 0)
